-- Japan, India, Malaysia, Thailand: Fixed-Income, Currency Preview for Asia
-- B y   A n d r e a   W o n g
-- 2010-09-21T22:54:27Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-09-21/japan-india-malaysia-thailand-fixed-income-currency-preview-for-asia.html
The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  Financial markets in South Korea, China and Taiwan are
closed today for public holidays.  Japan: Chief Cabinet Secretary  Yoshito Sengoku  will hold
media briefings at 11 a.m. and 4 p.m. in Tokyo.  Bank of Japan board member  Ryuzo Miyao  will speak at a
business meeting at 10:30 a.m. in Tokushima City, Japan. He will
have a press briefing from around 1:30 p.m.  The Ministry of Economy, Trade and Industry will release at
1:30 p.m. in Tokyo its report on the all-industry activity index
for July. Japan’s all-industry activity index rose 1 percent in
July from June, when it gained 0.1 percent, according to a
Bloomberg News survey of economists.  The yield on the 1 percent government bond due September
2020 was at 1.045 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co.,
the nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.  The yen traded at 85.10 per dollar at 7:50 a.m. in Tokyo.  Malaysia:  Consumer prices rose 2 percent in August from a
year earlier, according to the median estimate in a Bloomberg
News survey, following a 1.9 percent gain in July. The
statistics department will release the data at 4 p.m. local time.  The government is scheduled to auction Islamic bonds maturing
in 2013 this month. It may disclose the amount and date of the
offering as early as today.  The yield on the 3.835 percent bond due August 2015 was
3.31 percent. The ringgit was at 3.1005.  India: The government plans to raise as much as 30 billion
rupees ($656 million) by selling 91-day and 364-day bills.  The yield on the 7.80 percent bond due in May 2020 was
7.988 percent. The rupee was at 45.76.  Thailand: The government will sell a combined 23 billion
baht ($748 million) of bonds due 2019 and floating-rate notes
maturing in 2014.  The yield on the 5.85 percent note maturing March 2021 was
3.09 percent. The baht was at 30.76.  To contact the reporter on this story:
 Andrea Wong  in Hong Kong at 
